  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- Recommends policies and guidelines to countries\n- Monitors implementation of anti-money laundering measures\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide framework for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for financial transparency\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Most countries have their own specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Examples include the Bank Secrecy Act in the US and the Proceeds of Crime Act in the UK\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nWhile not a single unified international law, these frameworks create a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering.",
